On March 9, The Lancet, a medical journal, published a paper by Cao Bin, deputy director of the china-japan Friendship Hospital, among others, to explore the risk factors associated with mortality in adult patients with NCP, it points out that older patients are indeed more likely to die.

Although there have been articles on cases of NCP, the risk factors for death are not well described because many patients are still hospitalized at the time of publication, the article said.

The study included 135 patients from Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital and 56 patients from Wuhan Lung Hospital. Of the 191 patients who were discharged or died before January 31,2020,137 patients were discharged and 54 patients died. The median time from onset to discharge was 22 days and the median time of death was 18.5 days.

The most common symptoms at admission are fever and cough, along with sputum and weakness, and ground-glass infiltration of the lungs, the article said. Of the 91 patients included in the study, 91 had underlying disease, including 58 with hypertension, 36 with diabetes and 15 with coronary heart disease.

The study found a number of factors associated with mortality, such as Advanced Age, higher organ failure assessment scores at admission, and levels of the Thrombus Marker d-dimer greater than 1 ΜG / l.

In addition, this study is the first to elucidate the timing of the detoxification of the novel coronavirus, the time at which the virus infects host cells and continues to reproduce. In Influenza, the longer the detox period, the more likely it is that death will result. The evaluation of viral replication level and duration is important to assess the risk of virus transmission, formulate treatment and isolation measures.

The median duration of detoxification among survivors was 20 days, with a minimum of eight days, and in one case 37 days.

Cao Bin told the Lancet after the article was published, "The 20-day figure reverses the idea of detox times for acute respiratory virus infections, " said Dr.
